<!-- ARTICLE BODY -->
<main class="article-body">

  <!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
  <div class="main-content">

    <!-- SECTION 1 -->
    <section class="section reveal" id="sec-understanding">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">
        <span class="eyebrow-num">01</span>
        <span class="eyebrow-text">Understanding the Basics</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-heading">What exactly is a <em>slipped disc</em>?</h2>
      <p class="prose">
        The spine is made up of a series of bones (vertebrae) cushioned by intervertebral discs — flexible, shock-absorbing pads with a tough outer ring and a gel-like centre. When the outer ring weakens or tears, the soft inner material can push outward. This is commonly called a <strong>herniated, prolapsed, or slipped disc</strong>.
      </p>
      <p class="prose">
        The herniated material can press against nearby nerve roots, causing not just localised back pain but also radiating pain, numbness, or weakness along the path of the affected nerve. The lumbar region (lower back) is most commonly affected, often involving the L4–L5 or L5–S1 discs.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout--info">
        <div class="callout-icon">💡</div>
        <div class="callout-body">
          <div class="callout-title">Key distinction</div>
          <div class="callout-text">A slipped disc is a <strong>structural problem</strong> — something has physically changed in the anatomy. A muscle spasm, by contrast, is a <strong>functional problem</strong> — the muscles are working abnormally, but there is no structural damage (unless it is a protective response to an underlying injury).</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="section-heading" style="margin-top:40px;">And a <em>muscle spasm</em>?</h2>
      <p class="prose">
        A muscle spasm is an involuntary, sustained contraction of one or more muscles. In the back, spasms most commonly affect the erector spinae and quadratus lumborum — the long muscles that run parallel to the spine. They can be triggered by overexertion, dehydration, sudden awkward movement, or as a <strong>protective response</strong> when the nervous system senses a threat to the spine.
      </p>
      <p class="prose">
        This protective spasm mechanism is one reason that slipped discs and muscle spasms can co-exist — the disc herniation triggers the nervous system to lock surrounding muscles in spasm to stabilise the area.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider reveal"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 2 – SYMPTOMS -->
    <section class="section reveal" id="sec-symptoms">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">
        <span class="eyebrow-num">02</span>
        <span class="eyebrow-text">Reading the Signals</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-heading">Recognising the <em>symptoms</em></h2>
      <p class="prose">
        Both conditions cause back pain — but the character, radiation, and behaviour of the pain differ significantly. Learning to read these signals can help you and your doctor narrow down the cause quickly.
      </p>

      <div class="symptom-grid">
        <div class="sym-card sym-card--disc">
          <div class="sym-card-header">
            <div class="sym-dot"></div>
            <div class="sym-card-title">Slipped Disc</div>
          </div>
          <ul class="sym-list">
            <li>Pain that <strong>radiates down</strong> the leg (sciatica) or arm</li>
            <li>Numbness or tingling in the limb below the waist</li>
            <li>Muscle weakness in the leg or foot</li>
            <li>Worsens with sitting, bending forward, coughing or sneezing</li>
            <li>Sharp or burning quality, often one-sided</li>
            <li>Usually gradual onset, though sometimes sudden</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="sym-card sym-card--spasm">
          <div class="sym-card-header">
            <div class="sym-dot"></div>
            <div class="sym-card-title">Muscle Spasm</div>
          </div>
          <ul class="sym-list">
            <li>Pain localised to the back — rarely travels to the legs</li>
            <li>Visible or palpable muscle tightness or knot</li>
            <li>Pain that eases with rest and heat</li>
            <li>Sudden onset — often follows a specific movement or strain</li>
            <li>Aching, cramping quality; no neurological symptoms</li>
            <li>Stiffness that improves (or worsens) with gentle movement</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout--warning">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚠️</div>
        <div class="callout-body">
          <div class="callout-title">The overlap problem</div>
          <div class="callout-text">Symptoms can overlap significantly. A large disc herniation can cause severe localised spasm with no visible radiation, while a severe spasm can temporarily compress nerves, creating numbness or tingling. <strong>Self-diagnosis is unreliable</strong> — this guide helps you understand patterns, but clinical examination and imaging are often essential.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider reveal"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 3 – COMPARISON TABLE -->
    <section class="section reveal" id="sec-compare">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">
        <span class="eyebrow-num">03</span>
        <span class="eyebrow-text">Side-by-Side</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-heading">A structured <em>comparison</em></h2>
      <p class="prose">The table below summarises the most clinically useful distinguishing features between the two conditions.</p>

      <table class="compare-table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Feature</th>
            <th>🫀 Slipped Disc</th>
            <th>⚡ Muscle Spasm</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Pain type</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Sharp, burning, electric</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Aching, cramping, dull</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Radiation</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Down leg or arm (dermatomal)</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Stays in back, rarely radiates</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Onset</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Gradual or sudden (lifting)</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Sudden — specific trigger</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Neurological signs</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Numbness, tingling, weakness</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Absent (unless severe)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Effect of rest</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Variable — often worse lying down</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Usually improves with rest</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Effect of movement</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Worse with flexion, coughing</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Initially worse, then may improve</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Palpable tension</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Not usually palpable</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Muscle band or "knot" felt</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Duration (untreated)</td>
            <td class="td-disc">Weeks to months; may persist</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Days to 2 weeks typically</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Diagnosis confirmed by</td>
            <td class="td-disc">MRI scan</td>
            <td class="td-spasm">Clinical examination</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider reveal"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 4 – RED FLAGS -->
    <section class="section reveal" id="sec-redflags">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">
        <span class="eyebrow-num">04</span>
        <span class="eyebrow-text">Urgent Signals</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-heading">Red flags — <em>seek care immediately</em></h2>
      <p class="prose">
        Certain symptoms indicate that neural structures or vascular supply are severely compromised. These are medical emergencies — <strong>do not wait for your next scheduled appointment</strong>.
      </p>

      <div class="red-flag-grid">
        <div class="rflag">
          <div class="rflag-icon">🚨</div>
          <div class="rflag-text"><strong>Loss of bladder or bowel control</strong> — may indicate cauda equina syndrome, a surgical emergency</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rflag">
          <div class="rflag-icon">🦵</div>
          <div class="rflag-text"><strong>Sudden weakness in one or both legs</strong> — inability to lift the foot (foot drop) or stand</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rflag">
          <div class="rflag-icon">😴</div>
          <div class="rflag-text"><strong>Saddle anaesthesia</strong> — numbness in the inner thighs, perineum, or genitals</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rflag">
          <div class="rflag-icon">🌙</div>
          <div class="rflag-text"><strong>Severe pain at night or at rest</strong> that wakes you — could suggest infection, tumour, or fracture</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rflag">
          <div class="rflag-icon">🌡️</div>
          <div class="rflag-text"><strong>Fever with back pain</strong> — raises concern for spinal infection (discitis or abscess)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="rflag">
          <div class="rflag-icon">⚖️</div>
          <div class="rflag-text"><strong>Unexplained weight loss</strong> alongside back pain — warrants urgent investigation for systemic cause</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout--danger">
        <div class="callout-icon">🚑</div>
        <div class="callout-body">
          <div class="callout-title">Cauda Equina Syndrome — A True Emergency</div>
          <div class="callout-text">If you experience <strong>loss of bladder or bowel control</strong> alongside back pain and leg symptoms, go to the emergency department immediately. Cauda equina syndrome requires surgical decompression within hours to prevent permanent paralysis.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider reveal"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 5 – TREATMENT -->
    <section class="section reveal" id="sec-treatment">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">
        <span class="eyebrow-num">05</span>
        <span class="eyebrow-text">Management Pathways</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-heading">Treatment approaches — <em>why they differ</em></h2>
      <p class="prose">
        Because the underlying mechanism is different, the treatment strategies diverge substantially. Applying muscle-spasm treatment to a herniated disc (or vice versa) is not only unhelpful — in some cases it can delay recovery or cause harm.
      </p>

      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="t-step">
          <div class="t-dot"></div>
          <div class="t-label">Muscle Spasm — First line</div>
          <div class="t-heading">Rest, Heat & Anti-inflammatories</div>
          <div class="t-body">Short-term rest (24–48 hours, not prolonged bed rest), topical or oral NSAIDs, heat application to the affected muscles, and gentle mobilisation. Muscle relaxants may be prescribed for severe spasm. Most acute spasms resolve within 2 weeks with conservative management.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="t-step">
          <div class="t-dot"></div>
          <div class="t-label">Muscle Spasm — Recovery</div>
          <div class="t-heading">Physiotherapy & Core Strengthening</div>
          <div class="t-body">Once acute pain subsides, physiotherapy focuses on flexibility exercises (e.g., child's pose, knee-to-chest), followed by progressive core stabilisation. McKenzie method and soft-tissue release techniques are commonly used. Addressing the root cause (posture, ergonomics, weak core) is essential to prevent recurrence.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="t-step">
          <div class="t-dot"></div>
          <div class="t-label">Slipped Disc — First line</div>
          <div class="t-heading">Structured Conservative Care</div>
          <div class="t-body">Disc herniations are treated conservatively first: NSAIDs, neuropathic pain medications (gabapentin, pregabalin if radiculopathy is present), selective nerve root blocks, and specialist physiotherapy. Traction, certain manipulation techniques, and heat should be <strong>avoided</strong> in acute disc herniation without specialist guidance.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="t-step">
          <div class="t-dot"></div>
          <div class="t-label">Slipped Disc — Escalation</div>
          <div class="t-heading">Injections & Surgical Options</div>
          <div class="t-body">If conservative management fails after 6–8 weeks, or if neurological deficits are worsening, epidural steroid injections or surgical microdiscectomy may be indicated. Surgery is highly effective for true disc herniation with radiculopathy — success rates exceed 85% in appropriately selected patients.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pullquote reveal">
        <p class="pullquote-text">Most disc herniations improve without surgery. The goal of specialist assessment is not to operate — it's to ensure you're on the right pathway, with the right timeline, and with red flags identified early.</p>
        <div class="pullquote-attr">Dr. Sarish Sharma · Spine & Orthopaedic Surgeon</div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="section-divider reveal"></div>

    <!-- SECTION 6 – WHEN TO SEE A SPECIALIST -->
    <section class="section reveal" id="sec-specialist">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">
        <span class="eyebrow-num">06</span>
        <span class="eyebrow-text">Getting Expert Help</span>
      </div>
      <h2 class="section-heading">When to see a <em>specialist</em></h2>
      <p class="prose">
        Not every episode of back pain requires specialist review. But there are clear thresholds — and waiting too long when these are crossed can result in avoidable complications.
      </p>
      <p class="prose">
        <strong>See a GP promptly</strong> if back pain has lasted more than 2–3 weeks without improvement, if you have any neurological symptoms (numbness, tingling, weakness), or if the pain is significantly impacting your daily life or sleep.
      </p>
      <p class="prose">
        <strong>Request a specialist referral</strong> (orthopaedic surgeon or neurosurgeon) if an MRI has confirmed disc herniation, if radiculopathy is not resolving with conservative management, if you are a working-age adult with progressive neurological deficit, or if you have had two or more significant episodes of disc-related symptoms.
      </p>

      <div class="callout callout--info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🩻</div>
        <div class="callout-body">
          <div class="callout-title">Do you need an MRI immediately?</div>
          <div class="callout-text">Not always. For acute back pain with no neurological signs and no red flags, most guidelines recommend a 4–6 week trial of conservative management before imaging. Early MRI is warranted if neurological symptoms are present, symptoms are worsening rapidly, or a red flag is identified. Speak to your doctor about timing — unnecessary early MRI rarely changes management and can cause anxiety about incidental findings.</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

